defaultIn the Eos article, in which each of the co-authors is an AGU Fellow, we wrote
defaultIn addition to greenhouse gas emissions, other fi
defaultrst-
defaultorder human climate forcings are important to understanding the future behavior of Earth’s c
defaultlimate. These forcings are spatially heterogeneous and include the effect of aerosols on clouds and associated precipitation [e.g., Rosenfeld et al., 2008], the influence of aerosol deposition (e.g., black carbon (soot) [Flanner et al. 2007] and reactive n
defaultitrogen [Galloway et al., 2004]), and the role of changes in land use/land cover [e.g., Takata et al., 2009]. Among their effects is their role in altering atmospheric and ocean circulation features away from what they would be in the natural climate syste
defaultm [NRC, 2005]. As with CO2, the lengths of time that they affect the climate are estimated to be on multidecadal time scales and longer.
defaultWe also wrote (with respect to the 2007 IPCC WG1 report, but their focus was not changed for the 2013 WG1 report)
defaultUnfor
defaulttunately, the 2007 Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) assessment did not sufficiently acknowledge the importance of these other human climate forcings in altering regional and global climate and their effects on predictability at the regional
default scale. It also placed too much emphasis on average global forcing from a limited set of human climate forcings.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is documented in the p
defaultreface to the set of books 
