defaultconclude
default that
defaultMultidecadal predictions of changes in regional and local climate statistics have not shown skill when run in a hindcast mode 
defaultfor the past several decades.
defaultSuch a test, of course, must be a prerequisite to have any confidence in prediction (projection) skill of changes in regional climate in the future.
defaultPielke Sr., R.A., R. Wilby, D. Niyogi
default, F. Hossain, K. Dairaku, J. Adegoke, G. Kallos, T. Seastedt, and K. Suding, 2012: Dealing with complexity and extreme events using a bottom-up, resource-based vulnerability perspective. Extreme Events and Natural Hazards: The Complexity Perspective Geophy
defaultsical Monograph Series 196 © 2012. American Geophysical Union. All Rights Reserved. 10.1029/2011GM001086. 
defaulthttp://pielkeclimatesci.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/r-3651.pdf
defaultIn that 
defaultarticle we 
defaultWe discuss the adoption of a bottom-up, resource-based vulnerability approach in evaluating the effect of climate and other environmental and societal threats to societally critical resources. This vulnerability concept requires the determinati
defaulton of the major threats to local and regional water, food, energy, human health, and ecosystem function resources from extreme events including those from climate but also from other social and environmental issues. After these threats are identified for e
defaultach resource, then the relative risks can be compared with other risks in order to adopt optimal preferred mitigation/adaptation strategies. This is a more inclusive way of assessing risks, including from climate variability and climate change, than using 
defaultthe outcome vulnerability approach adopted by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). A contextual vulnerability assessment using the bottom-up, resource-based framework is a more inclusive approach for policy makers to adopt effective mitiga
defaulttion and adaptation methodologies to deal with the complexity of the spectrum of social and environmental extreme events that will occur in the coming decades as the range of threats are 
defaultassessed, beyond just the focus on CO2 and a few other greenhouse gas
defaultes as emphasized in the IPCC assessments.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is discussed in the articles
defaultPielke Sr., R.A., 2003: Heat storage within the Earth system. Bull. Amer. Meteor. Soc., 84, 331-335. 
defaulthttp://pielkeclimatesci.wordpress.com/files/2009/10/r-247.pdf
defaultPielke Sr., R.A., 2008: A broader view of the role of humans in the climate system. Physics Today, 61, Vol. 11, 54-55. http://pielkeclima
defaulttesci.wordpress.com/files/2009/10/r-334.pdf
defaultIn the text
default of the 2003 article
default, 
defaultI 
defaultwrote
defaultSince the surface temperature is a two-dimensional global field, while heat content involves volume integrals, as shown by Eq. (1), the utilization of surface temperature as a monitor of the earth system climate change is not particularly useful in evaluat
defaulting the heat storage changes to the earth system. The heat storage changes, rather than surface temperatures, should be used to determine what fraction of the radiative fluxes at the top of the atmosphere are in radiative equilibrium.
defaultI also recommend the 
defaultweblog post 
defaulthttp://pielkeclimatesci.wordpress.com/2011/09/20/torpedoing-of-the-use-of
default-the-global-average-surface-temperature-trend-as-the-diagnostic-for-global-warming/
defaultIn that post I discuss
default an issue (of deeper ocean sequestration of heat) that provides one (of several) major reasons that the global average surface temperature is an in
defaultadequate metric to monitor global warming and cooling
default.
defaultI would be glad to elaborate on the above issues, as well as provide other examples of the failure of the 2013 IPCC WG1 to
default properly
default report on climate science to the public and policymakers. 
